<br>
Sometimes a visit to the local library can be a very, very depressing experience. Flipping through history and technical books on the progress of the first half of the last Century, in varied of subjects as aviation, transportation or even expeditions to the South Pole one is left with a feeling of the emptiness, uselessness and non-directional feelings of the current age.  <br>
We have gone from the Industrial Age to the Service Age. There was a time once when we were all about exploration, conquest and colonization - we can now be defined as a civilization that focuses on internal problems that will or can never be completely solved. <br>
A cold shudder or chill may go up your spine looking at old black and white photographs of people, events, machines, inventions, proposals and visionary schemes from the 1930’s, 40’s, 50’s and 60’s.  <br>
To see what could have and should have been is sobering to say the least. That generation of yesteryear believed so firmly in science, technology and the progress of Western Man in all areas of life, it is easy to see why they have been called “The Greatest Generation.”<br>
They believed that science (understanding) and technology (application) would lead to a higher standard of living – which it did. They believed in letting technology solve its own problems (fission to fusion.) They believed in grand projects of engineering – Hoover Dam, Glen Canyon Dam, interstate highway system, California aqueducts, Apollo Moon program, large bridges, skyscrapers, etc. <br>
Today we are still reaping the benefits and comforts that these modern wonders have given us.<br>
However, when looking in detail at plans for the future from the not-too-distant past, such as the 1939 World’s Fair, one can only feel somewhat sick to his/her stomach in the realization that in today’s society we are more concerned with things such as saving a few non-native trees alongside a busy freeway that was built before the trees were planted.<br>
The age of the “faster, better and the new” has such long since passed us by that most people cannot remember when we passed it. Whereas today we drive vehicles that are in most ways the same as what people drove in the 1950’s, the informed historian of progress knows that we should have been using fast hydrogen powered cars a long time ago. <br>
The opportunity is gone, the regulations and restrictions grow by the day and the youth becomes ever more hostile to true progress. A phony war on terrorism, loss of freedoms in the name of security and the rise of the environmental movement characterize our modern 1984 type of world we live in. <br>
Yes, the Greatest Generation put into motion the processes which let us communicate via this very medium of electrons and photons. Their flame burned brightly for all to see and admire, I only wish it had lasted longer.<br>
While the rest of the world may be up in arms over some celebrity stealing merchandise from a department store, take a moment to remember and contemplate, least we forget the achievements and triumphs of the Greatest Generation. <br>
