vely entitled <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> High Noon: Science and Public Perception in the 1930s</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
Consider: In 1934, when the Corning Glass Works poured the 200 inch mirror for the future Hale telescope, there was enough public interest for Lowell Thomas to broadcast the proceedings live for 16 hours over a national radio network. Later, when the mirror was shipped to California on a special train, radio bulletins tracked its progress and people lined the tracks and cheered as it went by. <br>
In a speech to a crowd of unemployed workers, a California politician denounced the telescope for &quot;wasting millions when people were starving.&quot; He was pelted with rocks and garbage and had to be hustled away by the police.<br>
This was at at a time when people really were starving in this country.<br>
They saw science and progress as a solution to their problems, and not as a competitor for hand-outs.<br>
They were right, too. <br>
