An alternate view is that the very success of science and technology created a culture in which electronic  media, especially television, became dominant over the print media in forming public attitudes. <br>
The primary values of electronic media; instant gratification, high-intensity emotionalism, and sound-bite rhetorical appeals; became the basis for many public attitudes, with a consequent loss of the critical thinking skills necessary for an adequate understanding of science.<br>
The first view assumes that attitudes toward science before World War 2 were fundamentally naive. <br>
